Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is K-means clustering?
AI Response

K-means partitions data into K clusters by iteratively assigning points to the nearest centroid and updating
centroids as the mean of assigned points, minimizing intra-cluster variance.

Example 1.2

User

What is tokenization in NLP?
AI Response

Tokenization splits text into smaller units (tokens) such as words, subwords, or characters. Subword
tokenization (BPE, WordPiece) balances vocabulary size with handling of rare words.

Example 1.3

User

What is data augmentation?
AI Response

Data augmentation artificially increases training data by applying transformations like rotation, cropping, and
flipping to existing samples, improving model generalization.

Example 1.4

User

What is cross-validation?
AI Response

Cross-validation splits data into k folds, training on k-1 and validating on one, rotating until all folds serve as
validation. Results are averaged for robust performance estimation.

Example 1.5

User

What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response

A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.

Example 1.6

User

What is a decision tree?
AI Response

A decision tree splits data by feature values at internal nodes, with leaves representing predictions. They are
interpretable but prone to overfitting without pruning.

Example 1.7

User

What is a transformer model?
AI Response



A transformer is a deep learning architecture using self-attention mechanisms that process all tokens in
parallel, enabling efficient NLP. GPT and BERT are transformer-based models.

Example 1.8

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.9

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.10

User

What is regularization?
AI Response

Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.



